<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
So Pro, if a stronger guild conquers a weaker guild, that's not part of the game.<P>Say I'm a guild leader. My guild is powerful, another adjacent guild is weak. This guild is not allied with any powers that can threaten my existance. What would I do? Tell them to get out or we're kicking them out.<P>That's how a war-torn fuedal world works. This is nothing to do with powergamers/PKs/griefers/RPers/gankers what have you.<P>I don't really give a rat's ass whether my enemies roleplay or not. I do. But I still fight like a bastard.<P>Every player can fit under every label, depending on how they look at it. <P>Am I a PK because I kill enemies? Or because I occasionally whack someone when I've had a bad day?<P>Am I griefer because I offer my enemies no mercy? Because I won't let up until I've broken their spirit? <P>Am I a roleplayer because I have my own motives and my character has a personality and a background?<P>Am I a ganker because I try to make as many fights on my terms as possible?<P>Am I a powergamer because I want my guild to be one of the best?<P>All of these things are simply part of the game. It's like calling a FPS gamer a griefer or PK. <P>"You killed me when I was down to 12 health...j00 sux!"<P>The key to a RPer's survival in an online RPG is playing smart. I always go against the grain with my characters and make a feel that I prefer instead of the typical power template. Originality is a plus.<P>I'm a lousy PvPer. But I enjoy it. I find unorthadox tactics that at least surprise people occasioanlly and grant me a few victories. I use the fact that typical "powergamers" always use the same character (the 7xGM tank mage in UO, for example) to my advantage. There's a counter to everything if you're a little creative.<P>Ever make a character with 100 spell resist in UO? Ruined a tank mage's day really fast. That and a deadly poisoned dagger, maybe an energy vortex, you're in like Flynn. Not many people I met ever played like that...which is what made it fun.<P>Do I care that there will be entire guilds of PKs? Not at all. I'm sure I'll find something to break the mold should there ever be one in SB too. Overall, the smart will always survive. Half of it though is to learn to suck it up and enroll in the school of hard knocks for awhile.<P>Everyone is entitled to play their way. In a competitive environment such as this, you can still play your way, and adapt to the situation appropriately. A good example is the game Counterstrike. I'll get a lot of flames for this, but I got real tired of everyone complaining about the AWP. It was a good gun, sure, but not as overpowered as people made it out to be...just covering their own inability to play an adapt with an excuse.<P>I don't even use the gun, never really have. But I'll smoke someone who uses the AWP as a crutch -- what you might call the "typical powergamer" of CS. Gimme a scout, or a flash grenade and a shotgun. I'll FIND a way around ANY situation in a game, unless the design is so poor there's no way to (ala EQ  <IMG SRC="rolleyes.gif" border="0"> )<P>Anyway, Pro, thanks for inspiring me to get talking about this, it's about time for a new editorial. Everyone -- my advice to survival against players that go against your style is to do the same to them.<P>Play smarter, not harder.<P>--------------------<P>How smart is the average person? By definition, 50% of the population is <B>less</B> intelligent than the average person. Profit off this.<P>Morello
</FONT>
